00:12:16.310 --> 00:12:19.300
And I think this is a real
missed opportunity.

00:12:19.300 --> 00:12:22.140
When a user installs your
application, they don't always

00:12:22.140 --> 00:12:25.200
know exactly what it does
or how high quality is.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:25.950
And you've got a very
short amount of

00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:27.370
time to impress them.

00:12:27.370 --> 00:12:29.830
In fact, if the first thing
you show them is a sparse

00:12:29.830 --> 00:12:32.490
screen with a button forcing
them to log in, it's almost

00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:34.630
like you're throwing your
hand upward and

00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:35.900
showing a stop sign.

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:37.940
And I'm sure there'll be a drop
off here where a number

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:41.830
of users just don't even press
it there and carry on, which

00:12:41.830 --> 00:12:43.215
would be a shame, because
they'll be missing out on a

00:12:43.215 --> 00:12:44.880
great application.

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:47.720
So what we've done
here is we--

00:12:47.720 --> 00:12:48.340
if you want to go
to the redesign.

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:49.530
ROMAN NURIK: Yup.

00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:52.680
NICK BUTCHER: We've made content
come to the fore and

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:55.750
offered a different experience
when you load in.

00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:57.950
So Flickr is about
photos, right?

00:12:57.950 --> 00:12:59.160
It's all about sharing photos.

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:01.380
So the first thing you see when
you launch this app, in

00:13:01.380 --> 00:13:05.250
my opinion, should be some
rich, rich imagery.

00:13:05.250 --> 00:13:08.600
Flickr exposes a feed called
interestingness, which shows

00:13:08.600 --> 00:13:09.520
some great imagery.

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:10.900
So what we've done here
is we've pulled out

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:11.860
some images from that.

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:13.780
And this is the first
thing you now see.

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:15.540
So instantly, it's engaging.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:17.270
It speaks to what this
app is all about.

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:20.660
It's all about beautiful
photographs.

00:13:20.660 --> 00:13:23.010
And what's more, it offers some
functionality now without

00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:23.680
logging in.

00:13:23.680 --> 00:13:26.450
So there's a strong call to
action there to log in today

00:13:26.450 --> 00:13:28.090
with your Flickr account.

00:13:28.090 --> 00:13:30.410
But alternatively, you've got a
little hint there saying you

00:13:30.410 --> 00:13:31.750
can touch a photo.

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:35.360
And this'll take you right into
the core of the app, say,

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:37.450
viewing photos and seeing
comments on the photos.

00:13:37.450 --> 00:13:39.180
So straight away, we're
not logging in.

00:13:39.180 --> 00:13:41.670
We're exposing more content
to the users.

00:13:41.670 --> 00:13:44.460
And also, we hope you'll agree
it looks a little bit better

00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:47.540
at taking advantage of the
extra screen real estate

00:13:47.540 --> 00:13:50.390
available to you on this
larger device.

00:13:50.390 --> 00:13:50.860
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:13:50.860 --> 00:13:53.835
The one thing I want to point
out here, Nick, is Nick did

00:13:53.835 --> 00:13:55.660
the design for this app.

00:13:55.660 --> 00:13:58.790
And one of the things that
instantly makes your app look

00:13:58.790 --> 00:14:01.410
better-- and we've done this in
past episodes of the show--

00:14:01.410 --> 00:14:06.940
is just using different weights
of Roboto, different

00:14:06.940 --> 00:14:08.460
fonts in that family.

00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:11.626
So in this case, Nick, you've
used Roboto thin, is it?

00:14:11.626 --> 00:14:14.232
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah, Roboto
Thin and then Regular.

00:14:14.232 --> 00:14:16.560
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, so using
Roboto Thin is--

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:18.340
I just want to point out,
it's really great for

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:19.940
really large type.

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:24.340
So if you have something like
an initial screen that says

00:14:24.340 --> 00:14:27.520
"Welcome," or you want to
display a nice, big piece of

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:35.050
text, especially on a tablet
for like 48, even 64, 72

00:14:35.050 --> 00:14:40.588
scale-independent pixel sizes,
Roboto Thin is really awesome.

00:14:40.588 --> 00:14:41.520
NICK BUTCHER: Cool.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:44.490
ROMAN NURIK: So let's move
on to the next screen.

00:14:44.490 --> 00:14:47.750
And this is the screen where--

00:14:47.750 --> 00:14:48.950
actually, Nick, you want
to talk about it?

00:14:48.950 --> 00:14:50.540
It's the Sets screen.

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:51.450
Is that right?

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:51.830
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah.

00:14:51.830 --> 00:14:54.560
So once you get into the app,
once you've logged in with

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:57.410
your Flickr account, it offers
different views on your data.

00:14:57.410 --> 00:15:00.870
So you can see your photos,
your sets, which is

00:15:00.870 --> 00:15:03.940
collections of your photos,
folders, if you will, as well

00:15:03.940 --> 00:15:06.270
as seeing groups and things
from your contacts.

00:15:06.270 --> 00:15:09.690
So I've pulled out the Sets
screen here because, as you

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:14.310
can see, on the tablet, you
get these horizontal,

00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:18.530
full-width images which just
really don't scale up too well

00:15:18.530 --> 00:15:21.350
to a larger device.

00:15:21.350 --> 00:15:22.160
So we've look at that.

00:15:22.160 --> 00:15:27.850
And we've applied a different
kind of layout to really take

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:29.920
advantage of the real estate
available to you.

00:15:29.920 --> 00:15:33.060
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, so I've
just moved over to the

00:15:33.060 --> 00:15:33.950
redesign screen.

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:37.160
I just want to also point out
regarding those full-width

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.505
widgets, basically any time you
have anything that's full

00:15:40.505 --> 00:15:42.640
width on a tablet,
you have to think

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:44.050
twice about it, basically.

00:15:44.050 --> 00:15:48.660
Because that's just a lot of
space, not even for lines of

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:50.280
text, but even photos.

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:51.630
Photos are very, very rich.

00:15:51.630 --> 00:15:54.780
But when you have such an
awkward aspect ratio, like

00:15:54.780 --> 00:15:59.640
fixed height in a full-width
row, you don't really get as

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:01.240
much out of it.

00:16:01.240 --> 00:16:04.150
So yeah, Nick, do you want to
talk about the redesign?

00:16:04.150 --> 00:16:04.380
NICK BUTCHER: Yes.

00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:06.300
There's a few things
we've done here.

00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:09.270
Firstly, we've switched over to
a dark theme as well, as we

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:11.790
showed on the log-on screen.

00:16:11.790 --> 00:16:14.130
The thinking here is really
that, as we said before, we

00:16:14.130 --> 00:16:17.820
want this to be all about the
photos, all about the imagery.

00:16:17.820 --> 00:16:21.325
And having a darker background
really lets those images stand

00:16:21.325 --> 00:16:23.190
out, really makes them pop.

00:16:23.190 --> 00:16:25.950
So that's the reasoning for
switching over to the fully

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:28.520
dark rather than the light theme
or the dark action bars

00:16:28.520 --> 00:16:30.400
as we saw before.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:34.245
I've also moved away from the
horizontal swiping tabs, the

00:16:34.245 --> 00:16:38.590
swipey tabs, because that very
long gesture on a tablet

00:16:38.590 --> 00:16:40.900
device is a bit hard.

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:43.000
It isn't as intuitive
like switching

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.050
between pages of content.

00:16:45.050 --> 00:16:47.780
And by pulling the tabs out
right into the action bar

00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:51.880
where we have more space now
in this size, it gives you

00:16:51.880 --> 00:16:54.620
instant access to switch between
these four major views

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:55.900
of your data.

00:16:55.900 --> 00:16:56.755
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:16:56.755 --> 00:16:58.060
NICK BUTCHER: So the other thing
we've obviously done

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:02.640
there is we've gone to a grid
view to make better use of the

00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:05.630
real estate and switched
it up from vertical

00:17:05.630 --> 00:17:06.690
to horizontal scrolling.

00:17:06.690 --> 00:17:10.040
So as you can see, the images
are going off to the right, so

00:17:10.040 --> 00:17:12.440
you can scroll horizontally
and see more.

00:17:12.440 --> 00:17:15.290
This screen's quite heavy, I
guess, influenced by the

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:18.490
standard Android gallery and
applications like Google+.

00:17:18.490 --> 00:17:23.589
But we really hope we've
captured the spirit of Flickr

00:17:23.589 --> 00:17:25.730
and married it with a really
rich viewing environment.

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:27.790
Some of the minor details that
you'll want to call out as

00:17:27.790 --> 00:17:31.090
well is we de-emphasized some
of the visual information.

00:17:31.090 --> 00:17:33.910
I found using the Glimmr
application that there was a

00:17:33.910 --> 00:17:36.060
lot of information jumping out
at you, competing for my

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:37.990
attention from the photos.

00:17:37.990 --> 00:17:40.510
So, for example, if you look at
the visual treatment of an

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:46.160
individual set here, like a
folder, we've made it 90%

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:47.510
almost about the picture.

00:17:47.510 --> 00:17:50.340
And then there's a very
small callout saying

00:17:50.340 --> 00:17:51.440
the name of the set.

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:54.520
And then less important,
secondary importance, we

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:56.680
de-emphasized the number
of photos in the set.

00:17:56.680 --> 00:18:02.200
So we've used this relative size
and weight of text and

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:05.315
color to show the relative
importance of

00:18:05.315 --> 00:18:06.130
the information there.

00:18:06.130 --> 00:18:08.900
So I think this really makes
the photos stand out.

00:18:08.900 --> 00:18:11.090
And then, if you really want to
know how many photos, it's

00:18:11.090 --> 00:18:11.782
easily accessible.

00:18:11.782 --> 00:18:13.575
But it doesn't compete
for your attention.

00:18:13.575 --> 00:18:15.870
ROMAN NURIK: Two things I just
want to call out specifically

00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:20.170
that I like about the changes
here, Nick, is just in terms

00:18:20.170 --> 00:18:24.850
of padding and font treatment
or text treatment, you've

00:18:24.850 --> 00:18:27.050
given the text, like
in this case Waves.

00:18:27.050 --> 00:18:28.240
That's the title of the set.

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:30.770
You've given it slightly more
padding around the top,

00:18:30.770 --> 00:18:32.940
bottom, and especially
the left.

00:18:32.940 --> 00:18:36.610
And using either 4, 8, or
16 DPS of padding is

00:18:36.610 --> 00:18:38.270
usually a good idea.

00:18:38.270 --> 00:18:41.070
And I think that just helps
clean it up a bit.

00:18:41.070 --> 00:18:45.530
In the current version of the
app, you'll notice that these

00:18:45.530 --> 00:18:47.020
text labels-- and it's
very hard to see.

00:18:47.020 --> 00:18:47.810
I apologize for that.

00:18:47.810 --> 00:18:53.740
But these text labels, they're
scrunched over to the side and

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:56.520
squeezed by the top and
bottom borders of that

00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:58.070
semi-transparent black box.

00:18:58.070 --> 00:19:01.190
So giving it some more spacing
just helps bring it out ever

00:19:01.190 --> 00:19:05.140
so slightly so that it's
a little more legible.

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:07.920
So let's look at the
last screen.

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:10.780
And this is the photo
detail screen.

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:12.480
Basically, when you
touch a photo, you

00:19:12.480 --> 00:19:15.060
jump into this screen.

00:19:15.060 --> 00:19:17.080
And there, it's basically a
full-screen photo and gives

00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:19.160
you a couple of actions
at the top.

00:19:19.160 --> 00:19:22.330
Nick, do you want to jump
into your analysis?

00:19:22.330 --> 00:19:22.550
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah.

00:19:22.550 --> 00:19:25.040
You can probably skip on to
the next slide as well.

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:27.540
It's quite a simple
screen, really.

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:28.370
It's showing you a photo.

00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:31.090
But there's a few things which
I wanted to change about the

00:19:31.090 --> 00:19:32.120
screen, really.

00:19:32.120 --> 00:19:35.510
Firstly, I changed over to using
an overlay action bar.

00:19:35.510 --> 00:19:38.220
I hope it comes out in
the screenshot here.

00:19:38.220 --> 00:19:40.490
So that's basically, I wanted
the screen to be

00:19:40.490 --> 00:19:41.480
all about the picture.

00:19:41.480 --> 00:19:42.540
I didn't want to border
at the top.

00:19:42.540 --> 00:19:44.270
I wanted it to feel like
the photo was the

00:19:44.270 --> 00:19:45.290
most important thing.

00:19:45.290 --> 00:19:48.560
If you've used the application
as well, you can tap on the

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:50.450
main picture, and it'll
hide the action bar.

00:19:50.450 --> 00:19:52.890
But it actually has a slightly
jarring animation where it

00:19:52.890 --> 00:19:54.845
readjusts the size
of the image just

00:19:54.845 --> 00:19:56.170
doing a layout pass.

00:19:56.170 --> 00:19:59.170
And so using an overlay
action bar will negate

00:19:59.170 --> 00:20:01.625
that issue as well.

00:20:01.625 --> 00:20:03.770
The other thing is if you look
at the title of the photo,

00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:07.140
it's kind of burned onto
the photo in the image.

00:20:07.140 --> 00:20:10.565
Even if you go into the viewing
mode where you hide

00:20:10.565 --> 00:20:13.120
the action bar, this title is
still going to hide the image.

00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:16.930
So I've changed that and removed
the Glimmr name from

00:20:16.930 --> 00:20:17.705
the action bar.

00:20:17.705 --> 00:20:19.650
Because I think by this point,
you're using the app, you've

00:20:19.650 --> 00:20:20.570
got the icon.

00:20:20.570 --> 00:20:21.900
You know which application
you're in.

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:27.330
And just replaced the title with
the photo title there.

00:20:27.330 --> 00:20:31.090
ROMAN NURIK: I think providing
that sense of place of where

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:33.730
you are, that's really what that
part of the action bar is

00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:37.080
for, to tell you not only where
you can go and what you

00:20:37.080 --> 00:20:38.820
can do, but where you are.

00:20:38.820 --> 00:20:46.650
And so the action bar does
have a built-in title and

00:20:46.650 --> 00:20:48.100
subtitle feature.

00:20:48.100 --> 00:20:54.040
But in this case, Nick has
chosen to use a custom title

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:58.870
area that highlights that it's
a certain photo by the author

00:20:58.870 --> 00:21:01.850
of the photo.

00:21:01.850 --> 00:21:02.760
So let's move on.

00:21:02.760 --> 00:21:03.350
Sorry, go on.

00:21:03.350 --> 00:21:05.680
NICK BUTCHER: The only last
minor thing is I cleaned up

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:07.070
the iconography in the
action bar as well.

00:21:07.070 --> 00:21:09.950
I feel like the functions
it's offering here, like

00:21:09.950 --> 00:21:13.300
favoriting, sharing, is all
quite common iconography.

00:21:13.300 --> 00:21:15.950
So I felt like it cleaned it
up having it as just icon

00:21:15.950 --> 00:21:17.870
rather than icon and text
because you still have the

00:21:17.870 --> 00:21:20.500
long press to get a tool tip
as well if you don't quite

00:21:20.500 --> 00:21:21.710
understand what's going on.

00:21:21.710 --> 00:21:24.990
But I just felt like it removed
all those distractions

00:21:24.990 --> 00:21:27.220
away from the photo and
just simplified it.

00:21:27.220 --> 00:21:28.750
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, absolutely.

00:21:28.750 --> 00:21:32.660
So let's look at the other
facet of this screen--

00:21:32.660 --> 00:21:33.240
comments.

00:21:33.240 --> 00:21:34.750
Do you want to talk
about that, Nick?

00:21:34.750 --> 00:21:35.230
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah.

00:21:35.230 --> 00:21:38.070
Lastly, tapping on the comments
button or the

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:41.300
information button lets these
pop-ups which overlay the

00:21:41.300 --> 00:21:43.360
photo obscuring it.

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:44.636
And I decided just
to give that a

00:21:44.636 --> 00:21:45.410
little bit of a treatment.

00:21:45.410 --> 00:21:46.960
I wanted to carry on
that theme that

00:21:46.960 --> 00:21:47.875
content is king here.

00:21:47.875 --> 00:21:48.900
It's all about the photograph.

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:50.540
So I went for an overlay
style again.

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:51.450
So I hope it comes out.

00:21:51.450 --> 00:21:54.610
This is supposed to be a
semi-transparent pop-up box

00:21:54.610 --> 00:21:55.690
that comes up.

00:21:55.690 --> 00:21:56.770
And it's almost like
a toggle mode.

00:21:56.770 --> 00:21:59.500
So you can see here when you hit
the comment button, this

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:00.510
panel will pop up.

